oc:kn_0b2bba69 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When determining price points" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never set pricing based solely on cost to serve or competitor matching without understanding customer perceived value." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Cost-based pricing ignores value capture; competitor-based pricing ignores differentiation. Both lead to suboptimal monetization." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_508d0873 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When conducting pricing research using Van Westendorp" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Ask four Van Westendorp questions (too expensive, too cheap, expensive but consider, bargain). 2. Plot cumulative distributions. 3. Find PMC, PME, OPP, IDP intersections. 4. Recommended range is between OPP and IDP." ;
    oc:stepOrder 3 .

oc:kn_6702f789 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When structuring pricing tiers" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use the Good-Better-Best framework for tier structure: Entry tier removes barriers, Recommended tier is where most customers land (anchor), Premium tier captures high-value customers at 2-3x the Recommended price." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Three tiers provide clear choice architecture with the middle tier as the decoy-benefiting anchor, which is the industry standard for SaaS." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_7c733564 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When setting any price point" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Price between the next best alternative and the customer's perceived value. Cost to serve is only a baseline, never the basis for pricing." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Value-based pricing captures the maximum willingness to pay without losing to alternatives, while cost-plus pricing leaves money on the table." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_8121de81 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When executing a price increase" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Grandfather existing customers at current price. 2. Announce increase 3-6 months in advance. 3. Tie the increase to new value/features added. 4. Consider plan restructure instead of simple increase." ;
    oc:stepOrder 2 .

oc:kn_828cbbc8 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:KnownIssue ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When considering freemium vs free trial" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Free users in freemium models may never convert, can devalue product perception, incur support costs, and make future price increases harder." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Freemium only works when free users provide value (content, data, referrals) and the product has viral/network effects." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_a1580ccd a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:OutputFormat ;
    oc:directiveContent """## Pricing Recommendation
- **Value Metric**: {metric} — {rationale}
- **Tier Structure**: {number} tiers
  - {Tier1Name}: ${price1}/mo — {target_persona}
  - {Tier2Name}: ${price2}/mo — {target_persona} (Recommended)
  - {Tier3Name}: ${price3}/mo — {target_persona}
- **Annual Discount**: {percentage}%
- **Pricing Psychology**: {tactics applied}
- **Research Basis**: {method used}
- **Next Steps**: {actions}""" ;
    oc:templateVariables "Tier1Name",
        "Tier2Name",
        "Tier3Name",
        "actions",
        "method used",
        "metric",
        "number",
        "percentage",
        "price1",
        "price2",
        "price3",
        "rationale",
        "tactics applied",
        "target_persona" .

oc:kn_a385c1c1 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When evaluating whether to increase prices" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Signs it's time to raise prices: competitors raised prices, prospects don't flinch at price, conversion rates exceed 40%, monthly churn below 3%, significant value added since last pricing change." ;
    oc:hasRationale "These signals indicate the market will tolerate a higher price point without significant demand destruction." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_a5982ab8 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Prerequisite ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before starting any pricing task" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Check for .agents/product-marketing-context.md (or .claude/product-marketing-context.md) before starting. Read it to avoid asking questions already answered there." .

oc:kn_cf2034fe a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before starting any pricing engagement" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Before providing pricing recommendations, gather four dimensions of context: business context (product type, current pricing, target market, GTM motion), value & competition, current performance (conversion, ARPU, churn), and goals (growth vs revenue vs profitability)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Pricing without context produces generic advice that doesn't account for the specific business dynamics and constraints." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_d4b1a505 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When choosing what to charge for (per seat, per usage, flat fee, etc.)" ;
    oc:directiveContent "A good value metric must pass the test: 'As a customer uses more of [metric], do they get more value?' If yes, it's a good value metric. It should also be easy to understand, scale as the customer grows, and be hard to game." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Pricing that doesn't align with value delivery creates friction and either leaves revenue uncaptured or causes churn." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_f3454070 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Full pricing strategy engagement" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Check for product-marketing-context.md and read it. 2. Gather business context, value/competition data, current performance metrics, and goals. 3. Identify the value metric using the usage-value correlation test. 4. Structure tiers using Good-Better-Best framework. 5. Research willingness to pay (Van Westendorp/MaxDiff). 6. Set price points between next best alternative and perceived value. 7. Apply pricing psychology to page design." ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

